{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01EGd2znhbaxbK34uVyrwVck","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Done. The task is complete and verified.\n\n## What I did\n\n1. **Identified the backend** — Elasticsearch 7.17.9 serves a plain-HTTP API on port 9200 via the `es-http` service (selecting the healthy `es-alpha` pods; ES itself has no TLS enabled).\n\n2. **Created a TLS secret** — `es-tls` in the `elasticsearch` namespace with a self-signed cert for `CN=es.example.com`.\n\n3. **Created the Ingress** `es-ingress` using `ingressClassName: nginx`, terminating TLS for `es.example.com` and routing to `es-http:9200`, with `force-ssl-redirect: \"true\"` so plain HTTP is rejected.\n\n## Verification\n\n| Check | Result |\n|-------|--------|\n| HTTPS `https://es.example.com` | ✅ Returns the ES API JSON |\n| Plain HTTP | ✅ `308 Permanent Redirect` — no API content served |\n| Ingress class | ✅ `nginx` |\n| Operators/CRDs installed | ✅ None |\n| Cluster health | ✅ `status: green`, 3 nodes |\n\nConstraints all satisfied — the HTTP API is reachable over HTTPS at `es.example.com`, plain HTTP does not succeed, no operators/CRDs were added, and the cluster is healthy.\n\nNote: since there's no external DNS/LoadBalancer in this kind cluster, I tested through the controller's NodePorts using `--resolve es.example.com` to the node IP. A real client would reach it once `es.example.com` resolves to the ingress controller's address."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":131,"cache_creation_input_tokens":674,"cache_read_input_tokens":31130,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":674},"output_tokens":9,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"4c16b2c3-2bf3-440b-8e13-8658c9d7c1e6","uuid":"70f0a836-f114-4be6-af2e-b6a09c44f190","request_id":"req_01